{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646641"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:34:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18198"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18198"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10912"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10912","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10912"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18198"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64671"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25373"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe progression of intervertebral disc pathology follows a predictable pattern of anatomical changes. Understanding these stages helps guide clinical management and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical changes in stage 2 disc herniation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Free disc fragments in the spinal canal","Focal disc displacement with intact outer annulus","Circumferential disc bulging without displacement","Complete rupture of the posterior annulus","Internal disc disruption without external change"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStage 2 disc herniation involves \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal disc displacement with intact outer annulus\u003C/strong\u003E. The disc material creates a localised protrusion beyond the normal disc margins, but the outer fibres of the annulus fibrosus maintain their structural integrity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFree disc fragments in the spinal canal\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents a more advanced stage where disc material has completely separated\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECircumferential disc bulging without displacement\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes general disc bulging rather than focal herniation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete rupture of the posterior annulus\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in later stages when the annular fibres fail\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInternal disc disruption without external change\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents earlier degenerative changes before visible herniation occurs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe focal nature of the displacement distinguishes true herniation from general disc bulging, even though the outer annulus remains intact at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Stage 2 disc herniation involves focal displacement of disc material beyond the normal disc space while the outer annulus remains intact.","The nucleus pulposus remains contained within the disc space during stage 2 herniation but creates an outward bulge.","Nerve root compression can occur even with an intact annulus due to the focal disc displacement."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/","Lacroix M, Khalif\u00e9 M, Ferrero E, Cl\u00e9ment O, Nguyen C, Feydy A. Scoliosis. Semin Musculoskelet Radiol. 2023 Oct;27(5):529-544. doi: 10.1055/s-0043-1772168. Epub 2023 Oct 10. PMID: 37816361.","Janicki JA, Alman B. Scoliosis: Review of diagnosis and treatment. Paediatr Child Health. 2007 Nov;12(9):771-6. doi: 10.1093/pch/12.9.771. PMID: 19030463; PMCID: PMC2532872."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64671"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18198"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64671"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T10:19:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T10:27:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10912"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"ta